<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="241" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[810,1452,1129,2070]" pageId="1" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[863,998,1239,1265]" pageId="1" pageNumber="241">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in honor of our friend and colleague Edmund A. Jarzembowski. The specific epithet is to be treated as a noun in a genitive case.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="241" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[810,1452,1129,2070]" pageId="1" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[863,985,1348,1374]" pageId="1" pageNumber="241">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Forewing characters only. Eleven postnodal crossveins; discoidal triangle divided into four cells; three cells in subdiscoidal triangle; four cells between RP3/4 and MAa along wing margin; four crossveins in space between base of IR2, RP1/2, RP2 and first oblique crossvein; five rows of cells between MAa and MP; presence of a distal fork of RP2, below distal end of pterostigma.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
